Anonymous Sun 09 May 2021 22:11:37 No.38556132 Report
Quoted By: >>38557710 >>38558571
>>38555598
Read your shit over to yourself before you post. Always.
Read the dialogue and think to yourself 'does this sound like something this character would actually say?' if the answer is no, change it.
If you're going to write a chapter, for the love of God write it around something happening/make sure it forwards the plot. Sometimes stories do this thing where they just tread water without going anywhere or establishing anything and it fucking sucks.
Think up the ending before you begin.
Keep a picture in your mind's eye of what's happening. Imagine your characters and their surroundings in a vivid mental image and then describe the image.
Don't repeat yourself.
Look up synonyms for words you want to change. Don't feel pressured to use big, fancy words to come off as smart, but at the same time don't be afraid to use them where they sound natural and make the writing flow better.
Remember the tense you're writing in. Always. I'm fucking terrible with this.
If the story culminates in sex, then make sure it reads like a climax to story/chapter. A big portion of people read this shit for the sex, so don't disappoint.
Write it about something you're passionate about. Fantasy, sci-fi, 1920's swing culture, whatever.

Firstly, weak human MCs and perfect waifurs.
Nobody likes reading about a spineless fuckwit, and nobody likes Mary Sues (see My Obsession for a good example of actual characters)

Secondly, making the waifur just a reskinned human, (and no just adding heat doesn't count), for an example, take Tribes where it is said that the wolves lose the human perception of color to a canine state the farther away an object is.

Thirdly, and I cannot stress this one enough, make it readable. Edit, revise, edit.

And finally, if you can, run two stories at once, one with a "traditional" furry style species (Canine, Feline, or rabbit) and one of a more specialized species (Hooved animals, any sort of bird, other mammals and reptiles). This way, you can avoid burnout by bumping between projects.

You won't start off popular, we aren't in the age of "anybody can post a story here and people will read it". Now the OP is filled with somewhat well known names today, Reynaerde, Strong, Kaktus, Doph, Smiling, Fitewag, and Jacklin, but as we get deeper into the summer this will spin 180 degrees and the op can literally change in 1 day (I remember last year we had a day with 4 threads, and the OP literally changed with no stories on the first thread being on the 4th). Just keep working at it and more and more people will come to read it.


As for editing tips read every word out loud, if it doesn't sound right, it doesn't read right, if it feels like stuff is missing, its because it probably is, plan your entire story from start to finish, some method's I've heard was using flashcards to layout events, others do traditional storyboarding, and others still have a beginning, and end, and a come what may.

And remember, the same hammer that shatters glass, tempers iron
Be a man of iron

I have to disagree with thesaurus-anon. I strongly recommend against using words you don't know and use "personally", and not just because it's a bad idea to select bigger ones. The thing about synonyms is they exist at all because the differ in connotation, and connotation is kind of affective, like meme-meanings. If you pick a word because it "sounds better" and not because you're familiar with the connotative meaning, you're as likely to confuse your point as you are to further it. And further: people will be able to tell. Bad synonym choice is the literary equivalent of being a reddit newfag and needing to lurk moar.

tl;dr: synonyms do not actually share a meaning, they share a denotative meaning. That is only half of their true, understood meaning.

Anonymous Sun 09 May 2021 23:47:26 No.38558571 Report
Quoted By:
>>38556132
>Read your shit over to yourself before you post. Always.
Better yet, run it through a couple of different spelling & grammar checkers. You will gloss over things. Force yourself to really read it.
>Read the dialogue...
Read the whole thing out loud. No one is as good at pacing as they think.
>If you're going to write a chapter...
Slice of life has a place, as does a slow burn. But there has to be a payoff.
>Think up the ending before you begin.
Or the middle/beginning. If you don't have two of those three in mind soon after starting, the idea needs to incubate.
>Keep a picture...
This isn't always true. I write characters and dialogue first, then the setting. But when I get to that, it's all about interacting to show the emotions.
>Don't repeat yourself.
Another way to look at it is no two paragraphs should have the same information, and show the information in the same light.
>Look up synonyms...
This is really important for character descriptions. You can easily fall into a habit of recalling each character's three most visible traits in the exact same way. Like the characters themselves, their traits interact with the environment. What changed about her hair, her stance, her eyes?
>Remember the tense...
I have a tendency to sprinkle my character's thoughts with rhetorical arguments. It makes sense, it parses, but it isn't always the clearest way to present the final draft. The best choice is usually to not play clever tricks unless the trick itself is the simplest way to say something. This also applies to the active/passive forms.
>If the story culminates in sex...
This applies to all scenes and leads back to the third point.
>Write it about something...
Better yet, where your character(s) and you intersect without being carbons of each other. You'll do that more early on. Later, you'll use your passions to go sideways. That takes more research and learning what to not say.

But most importantly, write and learn from the experience!
